title: Suggestion For V5
body:
Hey @jdalton great to see activity here.

The past week I had started fixing up master and diving into the v4 codebase to understand the partial migration that had been started in master. I [figured out which tests are broken on master](https://gist.github.com/jonchurch/319c92547d7710ea1e6212db43b6412d) (not entirely exhaustive, excludes suites that fail bc a lodash method they tested was deleted) and in most cases tracked down the commit that likely did it.

I almost posted my WIP [Short Term Maintenance plan](https://gist.github.com/jonchurch/637aa1e601141cc27361b353852b164b) on Saturday, glad I held off! You've already knocked out items on that list.

## Suggestion for V5

I'd like to suggest a direction for V5 and V6 if I may be so bold. My _personal goals_ from my above plan and Step 0 were:

> ## Goals
> 
> 1. Get master branch to a state where it can be cloned and successfully run all tests
> 2. Ensure Github Actions workflows run tests on; PR opened, PR updated, push to master branch
> 3. Clear the way for contributions to Lodash v5
> 4. Document breaking changes that have already been merged to master, evaluate if they should be rolled back
> 5. Explore if the v4 release can be released without breaking changes from a fixed up master branch
> 6. Modernize master branch to 2023 package maintenance standards (debateable what that means 😂)
> 
> ## Non-Goals
> 
> 1. Release v5
> 2. Break v4
> 3. Open PRs that are impossible to review rigorously due to volume of changes
> 
> ## Step 0: Decide on Master Branch Direction
> 
> Due to breaking changes already in master, decide whether it will serve as the base for a new major release or a fix-up of v4. This will inform all subsequent steps.
> 
> Examples of breaking commits are (in order of earliest to latest):
> 
> - [3b4cbc70e7](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/3b4cbc70e7)
> - [5baad4df1015](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/5baad4df1015)
> - [bb7c959479](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/bb7c959479)
> - [3e2b0bb763](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/3e2b0bb763)
> - [aa1d7d870d](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/commit/aa1d7d870d)

### I'd like to suggest that the v5 release break only the legacy AMD/UMD module support, and avoid lodash method functionality breakage.

The more I worked on my fork at [jonchurch/lodash (js-test branch)](https://github.com/jonchurch/lodash/tree/js-tests) the more I thought about what could bring value to a new release. 

**The big question is, can we publish a v5 that does not introduce breaking changes to the method functionality?**

I want to see lodash v5:

* Use modern module systems (CJS and ESM dual publish)
* Drop support for ES5
* Update the DX for contribution to modern standards 
  * linting
  * github action workflows on all commits to master and PRs
* Use modern [package.json exports](https://nodejs.org/api/packages.html#package-entry-points)
* Export lodash.js as a barrel file instead of it being all in one to avoid publishing copies of all the methods as duplicated single files (which is what v4 currently does in the main package)
* Avoid breaking lodash v4 method functionality

These breaking changes are largely DX, package, and long term maintenance oriented. They also represent what I think is a logical way to break up development into something easier to follow and audit by the community. One new release with both packaging, test structure, support level, and functionality changes would be a pretty massive delta that could  get very confusing to follow very quickly.

The TS rewrite could also happen in this v5 release, and in fact might make the transition to a functionally breaking v6 much smoother and easier to migrate to.

Having a transitional v5 release like this could also make any fixes needed to v4 compatible code much easier. We can tell people to upgrade to v5 to receive any critical fixes, and EOL v4. Imagine having to make changes to v4 with the old setup, after investing in the new setup. I think having a modern v5 with v4 API support will make it much more pleasurable to commit and release fixes to v4 compatible APIs (but release the fix in v5 only).

Those commits I listed are a non-exhaustive list of breaking changes, but they are pretty close I believe. It might make sense to start master over with a fresh migration of v4, instead of attempting to revert the non-backwards compatible changes merged into master in the past 4 years.

## My Ask

What do you think? Do these suggestions resonate with you?

If offered help to achieve this functionally backwards compatible v5 approach, would you accept it?

Thanks for your time. (P.S. I'm fine with v5 using Bun for the dev runtime, runtime doesn't matter to me here)

title: The get defaultValue assignment operation

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
## Problem Description

`import baseGet from './.internal/baseGet.js'

/**
 * Gets the value at `path` of `object`. If the resolved value is
 * `undefined`, the `defaultValue` is returned in its place.
 *
 * @since 3.7.0
 * @category Object
 * @param {Object} object The object to query.
 * @param {Array|string} path The path of the property to get.
 * @param {*} [defaultValue] The value returned for `undefined` resolved values.
 * @returns {*} Returns the resolved value.
 * @see has, hasIn, set, unset
 * @example
 *
 * const object = { 'a': [{ 'b': { 'c': 3 } }] }
 *
 * get(object, 'a[0].b.c')
 * // => 3
 *
 * get(object, ['a', '0', 'b', 'c'])
 * // => 3
 *
 * get(object, 'a.b.c', 'default')
 * // => 'default'
 */
function get(object, path, defaultValue) {
  const result = object == null ? undefined : baseGet(object, path)
  return result === undefined ? defaultValue : result
}

export default get
`
function get(object, path, defaultValue) {}
@param {*} [defaultValue] The value returned for `undefined` resolved values.
## Problem solving
If the value is undefined, null, or an empty string, it should be assigned defaultValue

title: `debounce` with `trailing` set to `true` returns stale data for trailing invocation

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
## Description
When debouncing an `async` function in response to user input, the `trailing` invocation returns stale data, or in some cases `undefined`, **even though the original function is still invoked at the trailing edge**.

## Reproduction
https://codesandbox.io/p/sandbox/musing-pine-83tyzl

The above sandbox makes debounced network requests in response to user input with a `wait` of  250ms. It renders the debounced results to the screen, and `console.log`s the raw `fetch` response to the console. Using the sandbox:
- Type "ada" into the input
- We'll get three results for each character typed, and 2 network requests (one for the leading invocation, and another for the trailing invocation)
- The first two results will correctly correspond to the leading invocation (one fresh, and the second stale).
- The final result will incorrectly correspond to the leading invocation as well, even though the network tab shows that a trailing request was invoked with fresh data in the response.
- We can ensure that the stale data is not due to NextJS nor React caching of the request, as logging of the raw response shows that the fresh data made it to the client, but stale data was returned by the debounced function.
- Similar behavior occurs when leading is false but trailing is still true--a request is made and data is returned, but the debounced function returns undefined. [The documentation](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/types/lodash/common/function.d.ts#L374) specifies that this means the function was never invoked, even though it was.

## Environment
```
  System:
    OS: Linux 6.1 Debian GNU/Linux 11 (bullseye) 11 (bullseye)
    CPU: (4) x64 AMD EPYC
    Memory: 5.07 GB / 8.01 GB
    Container: Yes

  Binaries:
```

title: Avoiding Lodash version disclosure

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
As documented at https://www.invicti.com/web-vulnerability-scanner/vulnerabilities/version-disclosure-lodash/, Lodash makes its version accessible to the user through a browser's developer tools. 

This is reproducible by adding a dependency on Lodash 4.17.21 in a skeleton React.js project. In Chrome, go to Inspect > Sources, and view the `static/js/*.chunk.js` source, where you'll find a `kn.VERSION = "4.17.21",`, representing the version of Lodash in use.

I realize the difficulty in redacting this information since Lodash is a client-side Javascript utility library, but is there any way to configure Lodash to redact this information, or is it possible that it is not required and can be removed from Lodash?

title: Run trailing debounce when browser tab is closed

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body: A common issue with debounced API calls is that when the user closes the browser tab, the trailing debounce may not have run yet. This is a frequent cause of data loss. The `_.debounce()` function should avoid this issue by running the trailing debounce immediately if the tab is closed prior to the trailing timeout. This should only happen while running inside a browser because it's not relevant in headless runtimes (e.g. Node.js).

title: Run trailing debounce when browser tab is closed

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
A common issue with debounced API calls is that when the user closes the browser tab, the trailing debounce may not have run yet. This is a frequent cause of data loss. The `_.debounce()` function now avoids this issue by running the trailing debounce immediately if the tab is closed prior to the trailing timeout.

The implementation detects whether lodash is running in a headless environment (e.g. Node.js). If so, the new functionality is ignored since it's not relevant outside of a web browser.

Resolves #5689 @jdalton

title: Shouldn't mergeWith work recursively?
Replace MapCache with native Map or Set in SetCache

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
At SetCache, it uses only `set` and `has` methods of the MapCache class. These methods are also offered by JavaScript's built-in Map and Set object. Furthermore, SetCache maps all values to a constant (`HASH_UNDEFINED`), which essentially ignores the key-value mapping nature of a Map, and aligns more closely with the behaviour of a Set.

Therefore, I propose that we consider replacing MapCache with Map (or even Set) in the SetCache class. This could simplify the code and potentially reduce overhead.

title: `isBuffer` from `lodash-es` does not work in node.js

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body: Reproduction: ```ts import { isBuffer } from 'lodash-es'; console.log(isBuffer(Buffer.from("Hello"))); // false (should be true) console.log(Buffer.isBuffer(Buffer.from("Hello"))); // true console.log(isBuffer.toString()); // a function that returns false (stubFalse) ``` This is because of the line ```ts var Buffer = moduleExports ? root.Buffer : undefined; ``` Always evaluates to undefined within an ES module because `module` and `exports` are not defined in this scope. detecting node.js in this environment has to be done some other way. I'm not familiar with all the different targets this has to support, but checking for `process` might be a better way to detect Node.js

title: _.max does not cast to number

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
In plain old js `Math.max('1','2','11')` returns `11`
In lodash `_.max(['1','2','11'])` returns `'2'`

One could argue that type casting is not responsibility of lodash like in this [slightly condescending conversation](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/3477). **Which is correct.**

However in the lodashian spirit of erroneous types one should expect lodash to return `undefined` whenever the arguments result in an ambiguous answer, like when doing `_.last` of `Infinity` etc. Either this, or not have this function under the "Math" section. Maybe rename it to `compareAndGetLastElementInArray` or something and not let it pose as a drop-in replacement for `Math.max`.

In addition if you mix the types:
`_.max(['1',3,'2','11'])` it _correctly_ returns '11'

But if you throw in a 0 in there:
`_.max(['1',0,'2','11'])` it retorts back to '2' again

Negative number extort the same behaviour:
`_.max(['1',-4,'2','11'])` => '2'

All in all thank you for a great and extremely delightful library, however I'll probably look at other libs for math operations in the future.

title: Add isBlank and isFilled functions

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
_.isEmpty function only is suitable for `arrays`, `objects`, `null`, and `undefined` types. For example:
```
_.isEmpty(0)
_.isEmpty(false)
// true
```
And It has no support for nested empty arrays and objects:
```
_.isEmpty([null])
_.isEmpty([undefined])
//false
```
This thing can sometimes be problematic and cause bugs.
_.isBlank function will resolve this issue and give some features:
```
_.isBlank('')
_.isBlank('   ')
_.isBlank(null)
_.isBlank([null, []])
_.isBlank({{}})
// true

_.isBlank(0)
_.isBlank(true)
_.isBlank(false)
 // false

```

On the other hand, `_.isFilled` function does the opposite of the `_.isBlank`

There are the same functions named [blank](https://laravel.com/docs/10.x/helpers#method-blank) and [filled](https://laravel.com/docs/10.x/helpers#method-filled) in [Laravel Framework](https://laravel.com) which is very used.

title: merge description doesn't quite match expected behavior when using multiple source parameters

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
Take the following two examples
```ts
const foo = merge({bar: 'str'}, {bar: undefined})
```
According to the description: `Recursively merges own and inherited enumerable properties of source objects into the destination object, skipping source properties that resolve to undefined.`

So, as you would expect, `foo.bar = // 'str'`

However, this is not the case when using multiple sources:
```ts
const foo = merge({}, {bar: 'str'}, {bar: undefined})
```
In this case, `foo.bar = // undefined`

By the exact definition `skipping source properties that resolve to undefined`, 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/31498096/233504660-91a4e67f-0702-4ae9-8a5b-b262dd3e5f9c.png)
If you do multiple, source is not actually a parameter, so the definition is correct.

However, I don't think this is actually intentional. I think the likely intention is that any parameter in each subsequent source parameter should be skipped.

This is a dilemma for me... as I actually don't want undefined to be skipped, so this behavior is preferable to me.
